cs.FL, cs.PL, cs.LO, cs.DS, cs.THEORY. 

The paper deals with the extension of Antimirov's partial derivatives from regular expressions to $\mu$-regular expressions that describe context-free languages. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory). The paper also constructs a nondeterministic pushdown automaton, which falls under the category of cs.PL (Programming Languages). The proof of correctness and finiteness of the set of iterated partial derivatives involves mathematical logic, which suggests the category of cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The construction of a pushdown automaton involves the use of data structures, which falls under the category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper deals with theoretical aspects of regular expressions and pushdown automata, which suggests the category of cs.THEORY (Theoretical Computer Science).
